His message to squeamish chefs and foodies: delicacies like locusts and caterpillars compete with meat in flavor, nutrition and eco-friendliness.", "event": "TEDGlobal 2010", "language": "en", "language_swap": false, "name": "Marcel Dicke: Why not eat insects?", "slug": "marcel_dicke_why_not_eat_insects", "series_slug": null, "speakers": [{"id": "725", "slug": "marcel_dicke", "is_published": true, "firstname": "Marcel", "lastname": "Dicke", "middleinitial": "", "title": "", "description": "Ecological entomologist", "photo_url": "https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/b7bc482a93d07e39dffdf0031d3f47d29594d8e5_254x191.jpg", "whatotherssay": "Researchers have been unraveling [the] complex interactions between plants and insects since the 1980s, when Marcel Dicke says he was 'the first to show that plants communicate with the enemies of their enemies.'", "whotheyare": "Marcel Dicke wants us to reconsider our relationship with insects, promoting bugs as a tasty -- and ecologically sound -- alternative to meat in an increasingly hungry world.", "whylisten": "

Marcel Dicke likes challenging preconceptions. He demonstrated that plants, far from being passive, send SOS signals by emitting volatile substances when under attack by pests, attracting carnivorous insects to eat their enemies. Dicke opened a new field of research and won the NWO-Spinoza award, the Dutch Nobel prize. Now he wants to change Western minds about insects -- especially insects as food.

"People hate bugs, but without insects we might not even exist," he says. Dicke's PR crusade began in the 1990s, as a lecture series. Then his team made world headlines when they convinced 20,000 people to attend an insect-eating festival in Waginegen. Today, Dicke leads what he says is fast-growing research into insect agriculture, and predicts that insects will be on Dutch supermarket shelves this year. And does the former vegetarian eat bugs? "At least once a week. Locusts are nice cooked with garlic and herbs, served with rice or vegetables."

Read the UN's 2013 report, Edible Insects: Future Prospects for Food and Feed Security >>

insects, promoting bugs as a tasty -- and ecologically sound -- alternative to meat in an increasingly hungry world.", "whylisten": "

Marcel Dicke likes challenging preconceptions. He demonstrated that plants, far from being passive, send SOS signals by emitting volatile substances when under attack by pests, attracting carnivorous insects to eat their enemies. Dicke opened a new field of research and won the NWO-Spinoza award, the Dutch Nobel prize. Now he wants to change Western minds about insects -- especially insects as food.

"People hate bugs, but without insects we might not even exist," he says. Dicke's PR crusade began in the 1990s, as a lecture series. Then his team made world headlines when they convinced 20,000 people to attend an insect-eating festival in Waginegen. Today, Dicke leads what he says is fast-growing research into insect agriculture, and predicts that insects will be on Dutch supermarket shelves this year. And does the former vegetarian eat bugs? "At least once a week. Locusts are nice cooked with garlic and herbs, served with rice or vegetables."

Read the UN's 2013 report, Edible Insects: Future Prospects for Food and Feed Security >>
